{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Be3QGivu6bnxoJFb4oHE8i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I found the bug. The `_yr_scan_wicompare` function compares a \"wide\" (UTF-16 LE) string against an ASCII pattern. The correct behavior requires that the high byte of each UTF-16 character is `0x00` (since we're comparing only ASCII characters in wide encoding).\n\nThe fix commit (issue #1006) added `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00` to ensure that the high byte of each wide character is indeed 0x00, meaning it's a valid ASCII character in wide encoding.\n\nThe buggy commit removed this check `*(s1 + 1) == 0x00`, allowing the comparison to match even when the high byte is non-zero (like 0xF7 in the test case).\n\n\nLet me examine the full function to see how this check fits into the overall comparison logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":637,"cache_read_input_tokens":26869,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":637},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cde5cbb7-707e-4acd-929c-7a7d51ae0929","uuid":"40381df0-2b44-4299-996b-eb548b3668a1"}
